The embeddable class needs to be serializable.  Updating the definition of StudentId to implement Serializable (and adding a serialVersionUID), the issue seems to disappear:

    @Embeddable
    class StudentId implements Serializable {

        private static final long serialVersionUID = -7415410969017941320L;

        // ...
    }

Once I discovered this, I was able to do a bit more research, but it was of varying degrees of helpfulness.  For instance, https://stackoverflow.com/q/2726300/1281433, discusses whether *entity* classes need to be Serializable.  In general, they don&#39;t.  Another question, https://stackoverflow.com/q/9271835/1281433, is more relevant, but making the id class non-serializable there produces a different error message than what I was getting.  

User OndrejM,  in [a comment][1], pointed out [an answer][2] to https://stackoverflow.com/q/3585034/1281433 that locates the part of the JPA 1.0 specification that dictates that composite key classes must be serializable.  For completeness, the relevant portion from the later spec, [JSR-000338 Java&lt;sup&gt;TM&lt;/sup&gt; Persistence 2.1 Final Release for Evaluation][3], is:

&gt; ### 2.4 Primary Keys and Entity Identity
&gt; 
&gt; &amp;hellip; The following rules apply for composite primary keys: &amp;hellip;
&gt;
&gt; * The primary key class must be serializable.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/32852595/not-known-whether-passed-class-name-is-safe-using-jpa-embeddedid-with-hibe/32852596?noredirect=1#comment53566959_32852596
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/3588400/1281433
  [3]: http://download.oracle.com/otndocs/jcp/persistence-2_1-fr-eval-spec/index.html

